						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>6:6.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Law—Local ordinances</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287017102" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-2-221" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icf2a1fe074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-2-221</cite.query> allows judicial notice of records and laws of counties and municipalities. <eos/>
						<bos/>It provides as follows:</paratext>
					<display.quote>
						<para>
							<paratext>
								<begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>When certified by a public officer, clerk, or keeper of county or municipal records in this state in a manner as specified for county records in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017102" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-920" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icf2ae33074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Code Section 24-9-920</cite.query> or in a manner as specified for municipal records in paragraph (1) or (2) of <cite.query w-src-number="0287017102" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-902" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icf2ae33174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Code Section 24-9-902</cite.query>
								<?page no="163"?> and in the absence of contrary evidence, judicial notice may be taken of a certified copy of any ordinance or resolution included within a general codification required by paragraph (1) of subsection (b) of <cite.query w-src-number="0287017102" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST36-80-19" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icf2ae33274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Code Section 36-80-19</cite.query> as representing an ordinance or resolution duly approved by the governing authority and currently in force as presented. <eos/>
								<bos/>Any such certified copy shall be self-authenticating and shall be admissible as prima-facie proof of any such ordinance or resolution before any court or administrative body.<eos/>
								<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>
							</paratext>
						</para>
					</display.quote>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Under former law, courts could not take judicial notice of municipal or county ordinances.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7846f8a074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] Thus, a court could not take judicial notice of a county ordinance where it was not alleged and proved by producing the original or a properly certified copy.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78471fb074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] As indicated in the Code section above, judicial notice may now be taken of certified copies of local ordinances and they are self-authenticating.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Courts will take judicial notice of municipal charters, which are local acts of the General Assembly,[<footnote.reference refid="I78471fb174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] but not of municipal ordinances.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78471fb274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Local municipal courts may take judicial notice of ordinances of that municipality and such judicial notice would continue on appeal.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78471fb374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
